article.description: Senior guard Sean Harrington sank six 3-pointers as No. 12 Illinois rolled past Coppin State, 63-37.
article.headline: Cook scores 20 points to lead Illini
article.linkText: Illinois just Cook up storm in rout vs. Coppin State
article.story:
CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Brian Cook, the Big Ten's leading scorer,
matched his season average with 20 points as Illinois beat
Coppin State 63-37 on Monday night.

	   Sean Harrington added 18 points, all on 3-pointers, for the Illini
(9-1).

	   Illinois (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 11 AP) held an opponent to its lowest scoring output since
Northwestern had 30 points on Feb. 19, 2000.

	   Just two days after its first loss of the season to Memphis, the
Illini made 10-of-18 3-pointers, including one by 7-foot-2 center
Nick Smith.

	   The Eagles (1-9) frustrated Illinois early and went on a 7-0 run
in the second half that closed their deficit to six.

	   But a basket and free throw from Cook, a 3-pointer from Dee
Brown and two free throws from Blandon Ferguson pushed the lead to
14 with under 10 minutes to go.

	   The Illini led 31-19 at the half behind 13 points and five
rebounds from Cook and two 3-pointers from Harrington, who made his
first start of the season.

	   Harrington's six 3-pointers tied a career high set earlier in
the season.

	   Larry Tucker led the Eagles with 15 points. Deke Thompson added
eight points and seven rebounds.

	   The Illini appeared content to fire away from long range early
in the game, with four of their first seven baskets coming from
behind the arc. Cook changed that, scoring all eight of Illinois
points during a five-minute stretch in the first half.

	   The Eagles fall to 0-7 all-time against Big Ten opponents, and
have not beaten a ranked foe since a 78-65 victory against No. 6
South Carolina in the 1997 NCAA tournament.

	   Cook moved ahead of John Kerr into 16th on the all-time scoring
list at Illinois. Kerr scored 1,299 points for the Illini, and Cook
now has 1,310.
